mands were more complicit than others. Shepherd also reveals the reasons for the army’s early battlefield successes and its mounting defeats up to 1945, the latter due not only to Allied superiority and Hitler’s mismanagement as commander-in-chief, but also to the failings—moral, political, economic, strategic, and operational—of the army’s own leadership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCommand of troopsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar crimeszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaigns. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xOccupied territories. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zGermany. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021952440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300219524423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300219524/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles